snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp:
Learnings for freshers:
1. Don't learn everything, focus on important things and dig deep into it. Even 2 deeply learned ML algo is better than 10 not so deep learned ones.
2. Clear basics first, then move ahead. Focus on Stats, Python, SQL at start.
3. Be good at SQL, become intermediate in it. Will help throughout the journey.
4. Build quality projects related to different domain. ML, DL, NLP. Even 4-5 projects are enough before applying.
5. Build a good resume. Consider 2-page resume only if you have industrial experience before. Highlight metrics and impact of your work inside the resume.
6. Start applying in different sites, prepare for interviews, and learn from each experience.

*************** SIR PLEASE HELP ME (FINAL YEAR PROJECT ) ***************************
Project title: Using Visualisation and Machine Learning Technologies to predict the length of stay for patients when admitted to hospitals
Description:
Extended lengths of hospital stay are a serious drain on hospital resources, and the ability to predict the length-of-stay for each patient at the time of admission would bring various benefits for the NHS, mainly for hospitals resource management and planning. The development of efficient prediction tools will improve scheduling activities associated with the usage of wards and hospital beds, creating a positive impact on the scheduling of elective surgeries based on the expected availabilities of beds [1]. It is believed that the length of stay explains 85 to 90 percent of the variation in hospital costs between patients [2].
The aim of this project is to create a model that predicts the length-of-stay for each patient at time of admission based on their information available at the Connected Bradford dataset. A fully developed model would have the potential to answer questions such as:
‚ÄúWill the patient have a ‚Äúlong‚Äù stay at the hospital (> 5 days) or short (‚â§ 5 days) as determined at the point that they enter hospital‚Äù.
‚ÄúCan we use this model to predict what investigations will be performed in A&E from earlier data‚Äù
The development of an AI system for the reliable prediction of the length-of-stay requires access to different patient‚Äôs data, which could include patient‚Äôs diagnosis information (e.g. possibly based on the Major Diagnostic Category), age, gender, marital status, race, previous admission and discharge info, procedures, diagnoses, etc.
Workplan: Develop enhanced understanding of Stakeholders Requirements and Standard

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp:
Timing!
Kalse seriously baitha huu. Sochra likhra ki pichle 4 saal mai actually hua kya hai.
Aaj subeh tak click hua thaa ki yaar bachpan se huu level3. Smart but cannot-study-this-syllabus type wala builder.
Education bhi ajeeb hui hai, 4th standard mai realization aya ki ye syllabus pasand nahi, tabse side pe se self education chal rahi thii. Grew up with computers. Know and feel them like my own arms, but don't fit in when applying for traditional jobs.

Aaj realization aaya ki level 1 ke imitation mai fas gaya thaa. I am surrounded by overachieving toppers, aur imitation mai fas gaya thaa. Bachpan se suna ki ye future mai kuch bada karega, toh aur zyada fass gaya.

Ab wo peak jobs pe pahucha, toh pata chala ki bhalehi capability hai, par ye meri breed hi nahi hai!
Itne saal baad ab maturity aayi.


Thank you, proper shabd mil gaye feeling ko. Ekdum spooky moment hai ye.

Please correct me if I am wrong:

For the example you gave about the apples, the relationship is not truly covariance, right? Covariance is a function of strictly two random variables. However, in the apples example, the measurements of the number of green and red apples from each grocery store would be coming from ten different random variables. If however, we measured the number of green and red apples from one particular grocery store, but on different days - then this would be coming from only two random variables, and we could calculate covariance.

Thanks for the amazing videos!

Edit: Actually if you assume the r.v.'s of the number of green and red apples from each grocery store to be i.i.d., then we can compute the covariance, right?

I was blown away by your artistry and mastery of expressing statistical topics in a clear and appealing manner. Thank you for devoting so much time and effort to this. By the way, there seems to be a minor error in the calculation of covariance (the section between 7:30~12:00). The value of Y for two points (x = 24, y = 38) and (x = 29, y = 33) has apparently been replaced incorrectly. I think it should be modified as follows:
Covariance = ( ( 3 - 17.6 ) √ó ( 12 - 24.4 ) + ( 13 - 17.6 ) √ó ( 10 - 24.4 ) + (19 - 17.6 ) √ó ( 29 - 24.4 ) + ( 24 - 17.6 ) √ó ( 38 - 24.4 ) + (29 - 17.6 ) √ó ( 33 - 24.4 ) ) / 4 = 438.8 / 4 = 109.7
If it is wrong, please correct me. Thank you once more for everything.

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp:
Excellent video Josh Starmer

However it would be useful to include the data so everyone will check out the calculations.

Also if you make the calculations by hand using the information of the video someone will see that you get different results in comparison to using R. In this part it is not explained the concept of "continuity correction"

For example this is the code that illustrates the comparison of calculations by hand using R and the calculations produced by R using some data from the package ""modeldata"" about the relationship between the ambient temperature and the rate of cricket chirps per minute, where the results are different because of "continuity correction":

library(tidyverse)
library(modeldata)

# Data
data(crickets, package = "modeldata")

# Model
interaction_fit <- lm(formula = rate ~ (temp + species)^2, data = crickets)

# Using ggplot
interaction_fit %>%
broom::augment() %>%
ggplot2::ggplot(aes(sample = .resid)) +
ggplot2::stat_qq() +
ggplot2::stat_qq_line() +
labs(x = "Theorical Quantiles (z-scores)",
y = "Standardized Residuals",
title = "Normal Q-Q")

# cheking the data that generates the plot
ggplot2::ggplot_build(plot = interaction_fit %>%
broom::augment() %>%
ggplot2::ggplot(aes(sample = .resid)) +
ggplot2::stat_qq() +
labs(x = "Theorical Quantiles (z-scores)",
y = "Standardized Residuals",
title = "Normal Q-Q"))$data[[1]]


interaction_fit %>%
broom::augment() %>%
dplyr::mutate(standard_resid = (.resid - mean(.resid) / sd(.resid))) %>%
dplyr::arrange(standard_resid) %>%
dplyr::select(standard_resid) %>%
dplyr::mutate(n = row_number(), .before = 1) %>%
# Divide the standard normal distribution in n + 1 groups
# where n = 31 and n + 1 = 32 and find the values in the
# x-axis
dplyr::mutate(standar_norm = qnorm(p = n / (length(n) + 1), mean = 0, sd = 1),
.before = 2) %>%
ggplot2::ggplot() +
ggplot2::geom_point(aes(x = standar_norm, y = standard_resid)) +
ggplot2::geom_line(aes(x = standar_norm, y = standar_norm)) +
labs(x = "Theorical Quantiles (z-scores)",
y = "Standardized Residuals",
title = "Normal Q-Q")

# cheking the data calculated by hand
interaction_fit %>%
broom::augment() %>%
dplyr::mutate(standard_resid = (.resid - mean(.resid) / sd(.resid))) %>%
dplyr::arrange(standard_resid) %>%
dplyr::select(standard_resid) %>%
dplyr::mutate(n = row_number(), .before = 1) %>%
# Divide the standard normal distribution in n + 1 groups
# where n = 31 and n + 1 = 32 and find the values in the
# x-axis
dplyr::mutate(standar_norm = qnorm(p = n / (length(n) + 1), mean = 0, sd = 1),
.before = 2)

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp:
I'm sorry but your explanation is wrong. The confidence interval does not tell you how probable something lying inside our outside the interval is.
Confidence intervals are a frequentist figure and therefore once you have a confidence interval, it either covers the mean or it doesn't. There's no probability involved anymore.

So a 95% confidence level does NOT mean that 95% of the sample data lies within the confidence interval.
It also does NOT mean there is a 95% probability that new sample data will fall into the confidence interval.
It also does NOT mean there is a 95% probability that the true mean will fall into the confidence interval.
It's not even a definitive range of plausible values. In fact, large ranges of a confidence interval could be completely impossible.

The 95% and 5% are about the selection of the confidence interval (which is random), not about the data (which is fixed).
So a 95% confidence level means that if hundreds of scientists repeated this experiment and calculated a 95% confidence interval, then on average 95% of those intervals would contain the population mean. 5% of the intervals would not.

So if you do your experiment and calculate a confidence interval you don't know if it contains the true mean or not.

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp:
If I were to summarise it again:

NULL Hypothesis is the opposite of what we are supposedly trying to figure out.
If it says there is a difference, the null hypothesis would be there is no difference.
If the general hypothesis is that the coronavirus is killing 1000 people a day,
the NULL hypothesis is that it is not killing 1000 people a day.... it could be less or more but not 1000...

Have I understood it right?

The NULL hypothesis hypothesizes :P
that there is no difference between the two drugs.

If we see that the results are more or less consistent:

for example if the difference in the recovery time between drug A and drug B is somewhat consistent, ignoring random factors (that cannot be explained) -
It basically means that the NULL hypothesis can be rejected i.e there IS a difference between the two drugs and how they affect the recovery.

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp:
1. Test on : One categorical feature - Two subclass : One Sample Proportion Test

2. Test on : Two categorical features : Chi-Square Test

3. Test on : One continous(Numerical) feature : T-Test

4. Test on : Two continous features : T-Test (Correlation used here)

5. Test on : One continous feature and One categorical feature with only Two subclass : T Test

6. Test on : One continous feature and One categorical feature with More than Two subclass : ANOVA Test

In All Cases, Reject H0 if p_value(significance value) <= significance level(generally 0.05)
snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textOrig:
1. Test on  :  One categorical feature - Two subclass  :  One Sample Proportion Test  

2. Test on  :  Two categorical features  :  Chi-Square Test  

3. Test on :  One continous(Numerical) feature  :  T-Test 

4. Test on  :  Two continous features  :   T-Test (Correlation used here)

5. Test on  :  One continous feature and One categorical feature with only Two subclass    :  T Test

6. Test on  :  One continous feature and One categorical feature with More than Two subclass   :  ANOVA Test

In All Cases, Reject H0 if p_value(significance value) <= significance level(generally 0.05)

Very nice video.
Learning points of this video:
1. Test on : One continues features , Hypothesis on : mean , Comes under : One Sample Test , Name of Test : One Sample T-Test , Accept & Rejection hypothesis criteria on what scale comparison : p value



2. Test on : One categorical features - Two subclass , Hypothesis on : proportion between two class , Comes under : One Sample Test , Name of Test : One Sample Proportion Test , Accept & Rejection hypothesis criteria on what scale comparison : p value



3. Test on : Two continues features , Hypothesis on : correlation , Comes under : Two Sample Test , Name of Test : Correlation with T-Test , Accept & Rejection hypothesis criteria on what scale comparisons : correlation & p value



4. Test on : Two categorical features , Hypothesis on : proportion between two class based on other class , Comes under : Two Sample Test , Name of Test : Chi-Square Test , Accept & Rejection hypothesis criteria on what scale comparison : p value



5. Test on : One categorical feature - Two subclass & One continues feature , Hypothesis on : Difference of mean between two class(variance) , Comes under : Two Sample Test , Name of Test : Two Sample T-Test , Accept & Rejection hypothesis criteria on what scale comparison : p value



6. Test on : One categorical feature - More than two subclass & One continues feature , Hypothesis on : Difference of mean between more than two class(variance) , Comes under : Two Sample Test , Name of Test : ANOVA , Accept & Rejection hypothesis criteria on what scale comparison : p value

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp: Very true. I have recently completed a course with Times Professional Learning (TSW) in collaboration with IIT Ropar on AI & DL. Whatever you stated in this content was all mentioned to me. This was a 9 month course. The course name is Post Graduate Certificate in AI & DL from IIT Ropar. This cost me 1lac+. The batch limit was 45 students. 95% of the faculty was from TSW. All of us were professionals from various fields with experience ranging from 2 to 20+ years. Till now me & my other batchmates are still waiting to receive the certificate from IIT Ropar. The content of the course at the end was so tough that I couldn't complete as well they gave less time on it. There were 2 hackathon held which were below par. When I started appearing for interviews, I found that the course content is only useful if you are applying for Data Analyst post at Junior level or entry level that too not in most of the big 4 or faang or maang or renowned product based companies. If you are targeting for Data Scientist or ML roles or Data Engineer roles, pls take your experience into consideration in that field previously as well as do a free course. Build your knowledge from intership or YouTube. Don't do this course or this type of courses. You will be disappointed. Believe me. I am still paying my loan for this course & it hurts. I bagged a new job as a Data Analyst on my own effort bagging only 13lpa package. The work is good. I applied to 219 companies & appearing for only 11 interviews within 2 months after completing this course. I had high hopes from this course & it's outcome but I regret it. But now I am atleast happy that my misconceptions are cleared. Now I will not make the same mistake again. Now through my work I understand what is required to get into DS / DE / DA / ML / AI domain. I have started fresh again & building myself through contents available on internet for free & doing hands-on. This courses are not required. The companies do not care about this courses or certificate. Knowledge is what matters. Does not matter how you get it. Wish you all the best. Thank you for making this content, very valuable & made me realise that I was not wrong about this scams. Thanks!

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp:
I did this unconsciously where I was at school. I use to explain things to myself to see whether I have understood it really. It really works.

I would also add something else on top.
I did some further research when i entered university and found two techniques that goes in line with the feynman techniques.

Those are active recall and spaces repetition.

Active recall is basically the act of retrieving knowledge that you have acquired.
You turn your notes into a list of questions.
For instance
What is feature engineering?
what is feature transformation?
What are the types of feature transformation?
Why feature scaling is important?
How feature scaling is done?

Then, instead of reviewing your notes. You review the questions. You test to see if you still understand (and can explain it clearly as in the feynman technique)

Then, there is spaced repetition. This is the act of doing active recalling at spaced intervals.
For example, if you are able to answer a question during active recalling,
you can review that question after 2 weeks
if you are not able to answer a question, you must relearn and try answering it after 1 week.

Basically, it is about testing yourself on your notes(that you have converted into what, how and why questions).
But you are testing yourself more frequently on things that you have not mastered.

Now you must be saying all that is good but the system seems difficult to implement.
It isn't. There is the Anki app that does all the hardwork for you automatically.
You just need to put your questions and answers in the app.
Then, based on how you respond to the question(was it easy, hard, very hard)
it will automatically to the spaced repetition for you.
There are lots of videos on active recalling, spaced repetition and anki app.
Try look for it and see for yourself.
It worked amazingly for me to learn and make things stick.

import zipfile
import glob

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textOrig:
this is unrelated but I'm lazy to write the code to download and extract files over and over again so I wrote this to do it with the api command. I didn't include reading data as different data needs to be read differently based on formats, and many other obvious reasons. Use it if y'all are as lazy as I am. (pass api command as a string)

def get_kagggle_data(api_com = None):
    import zipfile
    import glob
    import os 
    from IPython import get_ipython
    
    ipython = get_ipython()

    code = ipython.transform_cell(api_com)
    exec(code)
    
    list_of_files = glob.glob(os.getcwd() + '\*.zip')
    latest_file = max(list_of_files, key=os.path.getctime)
    
    z = zipfile.ZipFile(latest_file)
    z.extractall()

Solution to the powerset question :

def powerset1(xs):

res = [[]]
if len(xs) <= 0:
return "Please Enter a parameter"

if len(xs) == 1:
res.append([xs[0]])
# print(res)
return res
else:
z = []
for i in powerset1(xs[1:]):
# print(i,[xs[0]])
z.append(i)
z.append([xs[0]] + i)
# print(z)
return z


final = powerset1('123')
print(final)
print(len(final))
snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textOrig:
Solution to the powerset question :

def powerset1(xs):

    res = [[]]
    if len(xs) <= 0:
        return "Please Enter a parameter"
        
    if len(xs) == 1:
        res.append([xs[0]])
#         print(res)
        return res
    else:
        z = []
        for i in powerset1(xs[1:]):
#             print(i,[xs[0]])
            z.append(i)
            z.append([xs[0]] + i) 
#             print(z)
        return z
    
    
final = powerset1('123')
print(final)
print(len(final))

super(MainWindowReceiver, self).__init__(*args, **kwargs)

I can open the gui by just instantiating with no arguments:

class MainWindowReceiver(QtWidgets.QMainWindow, mp.Process):

p1 = MainWindowReceiver(out_pipe)
p1 = MainWindowReceiver(pipe=out_pipe)
p1 = MainWindowReceiver(,pipe=out_pipe)
p1.show()

this is unrelated but I'm lazy to write the code to download and extract files over and over again so I wrote this to do it with the api command. I didn't include reading data as different data needs to be read differently based on formats, and many other obvious reasons. Use it if y'all are as lazy as I am. (pass api command as a string)

def get_kagggle_data(api_com = None):
import zipfile
import glob
import os
from IPython import get_ipython

ipython = get_ipython()

code = ipython.transform_cell(api_com)
exec(code)

list_of_files = glob.glob(os.getcwd() + '\*.zip')
latest_file = max(list_of_files, key=os.path.getctime)

z = zipfile.ZipFile(latest_file)
z.extractall()
snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textOrig:
this is unrelated but I'm lazy to write the code to download and extract files over and over again so I wrote this to do it with the api command. I didn't include reading data as different data needs to be read differently based on formats, and many other obvious reasons. Use it if y'all are as lazy as I am. (pass api command as a string)

def get_kagggle_data(api_com = None):
    import zipfile
    import glob
    import os 
    from IPython import get_ipython
    
    ipython = get_ipython()

    code = ipython.transform_cell(api_com)
    exec(code)
    
    list_of_files = glob.glob(os.getcwd() + '\*.zip')
    latest_file = max(list_of_files, key=os.path.getctime)
    
    z = zipfile.ZipFile(latest_file)
    z.extractall()

this is unrelated but I'm lazy to write the code to download and extract files over and over again so I wrote this to do it with the api command. I didn't include reading data as different data needs to be read differently based on formats, and many other obvious reasons. Use it if y'all are as lazy as I am. (pass api command as a string)

def get_kagggle_data(api_com = None):
import zipfile
import glob
import os
from IPython import get_ipython

ipython = get_ipython()

code = ipython.transform_cell(api_com)
exec(code)

list_of_files = glob.glob(os.getcwd() + '\*.zip')
latest_file = max(list_of_files, key=os.path.getctime)

z = zipfile.ZipFile(latest_file)
z.extractall()
snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textOrig:
this is unrelated but I'm lazy to write the code to download and extract files over and over again so I wrote this to do it with the api command. I didn't include reading data as different data needs to be read differently based on formats, and many other obvious reasons. Use it if y'all are as lazy as I am. (pass api command as a string)

def get_kagggle_data(api_com = None):
    import zipfile
    import glob
    import os 
    from IPython import get_ipython
    
    ipython = get_ipython()

    code = ipython.transform_cell(api_com)
    exec(code)
    
    list_of_files = glob.glob(os.getcwd() + '\*.zip')
    latest_file = max(list_of_files, key=os.path.getctime)
    
    z = zipfile.ZipFile(latest_file)
    z.extractall()

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp:
The artist's vector
Step 1. find the the vanishing point on the horizon, (A)
Step 2. About face exactly 180 degrees
Step 3. find the vanishing poing in your new direction that is on the horizon. (B)
Step 4.Draw AB
Step 5. Turn to a new dirction you havent faced yet.
Step 6. find the vanishng point on that new horizon (C)
Step 7. about face 180 degrees
Step 8. find the vanishing point on that new horizon. (D)
Step 9. draw CD with the intersection of AB and CD as E
Step 10. bisect angle AEC with RAY EF where F is the vanishing point on the horizon.
Step 11. rotate your body so you are facing your original vanishing point you are Facing A and bisecting line AB at point G

Your vector is Line GA with the direction of EF. , as long as your eyeball does not move, or you move, every point you see will have the vector of GA with a direction that is determined by other objects along the horizon.

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp:
In C++ programming language, there's a mistaken name that the container in the standard library is named "vector".
As a programmer, I don't think vectors are seen as arrays by anyone, `std::vector` is just a wrong name and have no any relation with vectors. Usually, you'll find "real" vectors and matrices in some codes about rendering, etc; for example, to render the game in the window, you have to do some linear transformations that change the coordinates from the world of the game into the window.

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp:
one reason we take basis vectors as (1,0) (i hat) and as (0,1)(j hat) can be:
lets say we take one basis vector as 2x+3y, now ideally it should cover every point on line drawn by this vector, i.e we can always scale this vector to point at every point on the line we get by extending it in both directions(by multiplying some scaler no.). But if we look at this vector, we can't make it's y axis 2, no matter what no. we multiply, because 2 is not 3's multiple (though we can get very close to 2). Hence we use vetors like i hat and j hat as basis vectors because every no is 1's multiple.
Please correct me if I am thinking of this in a wrong way.

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp: Definition answer (my attempt): The basis of a vector space is comprised of those vectors which can be combined via linear combinations to span the entire space (i.e. √Æ,j,k for 3 space). The vectors should be linearly independent so as to reduce redundancy ‚Äî if they are all linearly independent, these vectors span the space in as little vectors as needed.

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp:
The last clip of the video before it ends, now it all makes sense to finally define the basis of a vector space.
If the set of basis vectors are linearly independent, by definition, their linear combination only has the trivial solution of a=b=c=0 (a, b, c are scalars) to get the 0 vector. By this, we cannot at all represent ANY vector in the given set as a linear combination of the others by algebraic manipulation of the definition as division by zero will occur if we try to do so, and the vectors in the set always seem to add up a new dimension whenever we introduce new ones in the set, showing how they span over the entire vector space (hence the set is called a span or a spanning set).

I really thank you sir for making intuitive videos like these :D

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp: Imo matrices have two contexts, one is for a function and second is for a pack of vectors, so when you are making a composition.The matrix on the right is always considered as function and one in the left is always a pack of vectors, so you are applying the matrix on the left to the matrix on the right, but never vice versa. In the A(BC) example, first you get a new D matrix from applying B to C ( D = BC ), then get a result (R) by applying A to D  ( R = AD ). The same way in the (AB)C example, first you apply A to B then get E matrix ( E = AB ), then get a result by applying E to C ( R = EC ). Notice that you never apply a matrix on the right to the matrix on the left no matter how far from each other they stand. For example neither C is being applied to composition that includes B or A, nor the B is being applied to A. This leads to A(BC) = (AB)C. This is my vision only, so it may look silly for the most.

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp:
You can also see that as a sequence.

For example:
square, increment, double

You can imagine it's a factory line and you could "square and increment" then "double":
3->10->20
You can also "square" then "increment and double"
3->9->20

It's just that you did put one different part of the production line in a big box, but ultimately, you are still doing the same processing in the same order. So, it's associative!

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp:
It took me a while to understand the point he was making(with regards to how projection occurs), but it makes sense in the context of previous chapters:

(3-D Example below, but it generalizes pretty intuitively imo)

1) Linear Transformations and Matrix Multiplication‚Üí Multiplying two matrices can be conceptualized as applying one linear transformation after another. I will make sense of the dot product in this context.

2) Column Space‚Üí The non-square vector on the right side of the dot product has column space one(rank = 1); thus, applying it as a linear transformation will shrink your original vector down into 1-dimensional space. ‚Üí This is what Grant was getting at using √ª as the basis vector for 1-dimensional space.

3) Basis‚Üí The non-square matrix on the left can be conceptualized as the linearly-transformed √Æ-intermediate, ƒµ-intermediate, and kÃÇ-intermediate coordinates(where the basis vectors land during the second linear transformation). The non-square matrix on the right can be conceptualized as just 1 basis vector(√ª) with 3 coordinates of landing.

4) Dot Product‚Üí Conceptualized as the projection of a 3-d vector onto 1-d space(the right matrix) where the product of transformed basis vectors(left matrix * right matrix) determines the extent to which each dimension contributes.

*What this means‚Üí *
1) The dot product represents the extent to which 2-vectors combine in each dimension, represented by a singular value.
2) Column vectors can be conceptualized as a linear transformation from n-dimensional space onto 1-dimensional space.

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp:
Late Comment here, 3:42 is a clear demonstration of Thales' Intercept theorem. 2v projects a line that is parallel to v's projection, so the projection also scales by 2. In the first case, w's projection onto v didn't change, so in the end you just multiplied by V, then 2( because you doubled the v vector). In the latter case, v vector's projection also doubles due to the theorem, and is multiplied by w vector. In the end, in both operations, the original symmetric case's result was multiplied by 2.

Also, I only understood the parts following 5:46 given that the original 2x2 matrix formed by i hat and j hat had a row of 0s, since both now share the same coordinates, but vary in magnitude. In these cases, a dimension is removed, given that you aren't calculating anything on this second dimension anymore, so it becomes a 1x2 as usual.

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp: Hi 3Blue1Brown! Once again thank you for your excellent linear algebra tutorial. However, i don't agree with this interpretation. It is not coherent with other manipulations, like matrix - matrix multiplication, and doesn't explain clearly what it is the result we get. Let me share my explanation of what dot product actually is. Dot product is a special case of matrix-matrix multiplication, that translates a vector to 1-dimensional space. If we multiply w and v, then the result is orientation and magnitude of projection of the vector w on vector v expressed in units of this new space. The implication of this understanding is very broad - it better explains and makes coherent other concepts, like null spaces, determinants, asf. It makes also the way how dot product is calculated immediately obvious. Let's try this, please. As it was said, matrix multiplication changes orientation and length of unit vectors. On the example of this video, try to project i-hat and j-hat onto second vectors. Specify the unit vector as equal to projection of j-hat and 1/3 of i-hat. And now, observe, what is the magnitude of projection of w on v expressed in units of v, and how you would calculate it without knowing, how to perform dot product. It is self-explanatory, do you agree? The missing part is base unit of this new dimension. If we get it, then everything is very simple. Also, i said, that dot product is a special case of matrix multiplication. If we understand matrix multiplication as switching from one space defined by some set of coordinates to another space defined by another set of coordinates, then this is obvious, that what we need is a series of dot products in order to project coordinates from first space to coordinates of second space. Another implication, that simplifies a lot, is that by any transformation the observed object, f.i. a vector, doesn't change. The way we perceive the object in new space changes, the object is still the same. And this is coherent with the observation from real world. Let's say, that we observe two trees. If we come closer to the trees, they don't become bigger, but their magnitude in our new point of observation. When we come closer and we specify our distance to the trees as the same number of units, then those units becomes smaller, and the height of the trees expressed in those new units is bigger. If we change the angle of observation, then we change the projection of distance between the trees projected on the coordinate that is perpendicular to our direction to the trees, but the real distance between the trees stays the same. If we stay in line with the trees, we are able to see only the first tree, the second tree and all trees that are inline land in null space. We can't see them, but it doesn't mean, that they doesn't exist. We can also try something else. Let's take a pen, keep it in hand and close your one eye. Then, keep the pen in the same place, but move you head and watch the pen from different angles and from different distances. The pen is all the time the same, but it's perceived orientation and length changes. This is what we get performing dot product.

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp:
So there are two ways of understanding the dot product. It can be thought of as two basis vectors on the same number line that can be scaled to any magnitude or direction in order to end up at a specific point on said number line.

Or, the way that seemed way less intuitive to me at first, the "projection". At first, I couldn't understand what this one meant because it didn't seem to make sense. It seemed like, in order to project one vector onto another vector, there had to be some trigonometry involved which didn't make sense given that the formula was, simply, multiply and add. To me, this way of thinking of the dot product is less of a projection and more of a way to describe the "movement" of a vector in any given direction relative to another vector.

So if you have a vector V = [3, 2] and W = [1, 0]. The dot product of the two would be 3. This is because V "moves" in the direction of W with a magnitude of 3. If you have a vector U = [0, 1], V "moves" by a magnitude of 2, relative to U. You can create a circle of vectors with a radius of 1 that extends out from the origin and each of those can be used to describe the "magnitude" of the movement of V in any given direction relative to one of those vectors. The thing is, all of these vectors are equal to 1, so for any other vector, besides describing the movement of V in the direction of said vector, this "magnitude" is also going to be scaled by some amount, and this change is described by the dot product formula.

This was just my way of conceptualizing it and coming to understand what was meant by "projection". I hope this helped someone, but if it didn't and just confused you more... uh... unlearn it :)

Cheers

snippet_topLevelComment_snippet_textDisp:
Okay, I don't know if I did everything right but this is the last exercise:

1. Multiply matrix A by the eigenbasis (the matrix with the eigenvectors)
2. Notice that by multiplying you scaled up the left vector, with the golden ratio(approx 1.618), and the right by -1.618
3. Take that ratio into a third matrix(1.618, 0 | 0, -1.618) - (a diagonal matrix), call this matrix phi
4. This means that A = eigenbasis * phi matrix * eigenbasis^-1

Finally, A^n = eigenbasis * phi^n * eigenbasis ^ -1

Notice that the eigenbasis cancels out when we multiply so we only have to worry about phi^n.

If we write it all out we get: [0, 1 | 1, 1]^n = [2, 2 | 1 + sqrt(5), 1 - sqrt(5)] * [1.618^n, 0 | 0, -1.618^n] * [2, 2 | 1 + sqrt(5), 1 - sqrt(5)]^n
